I am encountering a soft lockup in the empty_rx_fifo() function due to a continuous while loop. The relevant code is:

#include <linux/io.h>
#define FIFO_STATUS 0x0014
#define FIFO_MAN_READ 0x0015
#define RX_FIFO_EMPTY 0x01

static inline uint16_t read16_shifted(void __iomem *addr, u32 offset)
{
    void __iomem *target_addr = addr + (offset << 1);
    return readw(target_addr);
}

void empty_rx_fifo(void __iomem *addr)
{
    while (!(read16_shifted(addr, FIFO_STATUS) & RX_FIFO_EMPTY)) {
        read16_shifted(addr, FIFO_MAN_READ);
    }
}

The kernel log shows:
watchdog: BUG: soft lockup - CPU#0 stuck for 23s!
RIP: 0010:read16_shifted+0x11/0x20

My hardware does not support interrupts. How can I modify the loop to prevent CPU hogging and resolve the soft lockup?

answer:
Add udelay() after a few iterations of the loop to yield the CPU. For example:

void empty_rx_fifo(void __iomem *addr)
{
    int iteration = 0;
    while (!(read16_shifted(addr, FIFO_STATUS) & RX_FIFO_EMPTY)) {
        read16_shifted(addr, FIFO_MAN_READ);
        if (++iteration % 10 == 0) {
            udelay(100);
            cond_resched();
        }
    }
}
This allows the CPU to handle other tasks and avoids triggering the soft lockup detector.

